Chaplains support the commander. They can be perfectly inclusive while following the restrictions of their denomination. Make them work for you. 

Partially biased, having been raised by a chaplain turned retired twitter troll (much love, dad). @ArmyChaplains

name: Peter Norris
tweet: Chaplains are a weapon system (without weapons). If the one you have doesn’t work right, it’s not the system, you just don’t have a Chaplain Kołek like we do. Counsel as appropriate, or DX the one you have and upgrade. 8/n

name: Peter Norris
tweet: Every weapon system we have has limitations. Artillery never shows up right when you want it to. Rifles don’t quite shoot as far as you want. Air defense assets in the BCT don’t... never mind. 7/n

name: Peter Norris
tweet: You can get lost in a rabbit hole about what you don’t like about the chaplaincy. This chaplain won’t marry these two people, this one won’t give that soldier communion, this one doesn’t circumcise people in the field, etc. 6/n

name: Peter Norris
tweet: The chaplain is not here to convert anyone. He is not here to exclude anyone. He is not here to run the MWR program. Chaplains, when used properly, help to make a unit a family. They make good commanders great. 5/n

name: Peter Norris
tweet: He is equipped to provide religious services to those of his congregation, and prepared to facilitate arrangements for those from any faith group. Soldiers seek out the chaplain and his assistant because of the confidentiality they have. 4/n

name: Peter Norris
tweet: There is time built into my calendar to speak with and hear from the chaplain. He has the freedom to help me see myself with candid feedback on how my words and actions affect others. 3/n

name: Peter Norris
tweet: The chaplain is a staff officer that serves as a special advisor to me as a commander. He sees things in the formation that I would never see, while respecting the confidentiality of those he counsels. 2/n

name: Peter Norris
tweet: I missed the pro/anti Chaplaincy threads last week. This is Chaplain Kołek (from Poland, but not this part of Poland), the 1-35 Armor Chaplain, and perhaps the finest battalion chaplain I’ve ever worked with. 1/n pic.twitter.com/f1vjijkUcB
